segments.text: We were talking about the second method course that we have and I was telling you that in that one we cover about five, six different topics and one is the land use transportation methods and it's a little perhaps mathematical and theoretical but the intention is that to cover the concepts
which would be helpful for planners to understand the urban and especially the regional area.
By regional, I mean like Dallas-Fort Worth region.
I don't mean big regions like Texas, etc.
And I found out that that is very much helpful for planners to go through that exposition to understand all those theories.
And then another topic of importance is

evaluation we go through the basically cost benefit type of things and we have exercises to do and in fact the planning related exercise to go through I think that's very important for them to basically to be exposed to
Then we have population and employment projection methods, which I think any planner should be able to do rough calculation of the projection of what's going to happen in the future.
Do you use cohort?
The cohort survival and also the trend analysis of linear trend, curve linear trends, etc.
Their formulation, how to do it.
In fact, there is an assignment for them to do that, to do these type of things.
Do they do it by hand, or do they use a computer program?
No, in this course, no computer.
Computer is mostly in the statistics course, and they do basically...
I have cut all the proofs, et cetera, in the statistics course, as basically to...
I'm presenting them where...

the conceptual things that in my mind they need to know but there are five major computer assignments that they put together data and basically starting from the simplest one they do one by one and get to the regression assignment which is the most complex one and then we repeat the regression assignment also in the second method course as just the review

just again because of my own view that I think regression is the most applied and close to planning and can be applied and they put together some planning related one in the second course and basically do that here they learn both a major statistical package computer package both courses I mean and also they go and apply that so hopefully they're gonna become efficient with that but then rest of the course all the assignments are manual like that

population projection one is a manual one and then the evaluation one which is a major development case in the downtown and they're going to evaluate to see if does it work to make to basically build it it is for cities like a parking structure or something a feasibility study basically to see is it beneficial for them to they have a piece of land and they're gonna see that if it is good for them to build a big parking structure public parking

or would be better for them to sell to someone else to make an office building or whatever something like that but there's so many issues involved like transportation they have a rail system coming and the benefit of putting a parking here versus reducing the
rail, transit riders, etc.
Then we have overview of shift and share and input output, those type of regional economic analysis that I thought the concepts is necessary for them.
We have review of linear programming in a sense that linear programming in some senses are exactly planning because you want to maximize the benefits to the society
under given such constants, and that is basically the definition of planning.
And then you have a methodology that basically does that.
Again, we don't want to make them applied linear programmers or something.
We just want them to know that there is such a concept very similar to planning and a basic mathematical concept that can be done.
There are a bunch of these type of small methods.
I have written a small paper, which unfortunately I haven't been able to publish that.
We're basically going through my philosophy of the method courses for planning.
If you are interested, I can provide you with a copy.
Yeah, I'd like that very much.
I used to teach the course in methods and techniques at A&M.
So here is another architect teaching.
It was a course that I came to enjoy, but I was backed into it because no one else wanted to teach it.
And so I had to become familiar with demographic forecasting and different economic-based theories and whatnot.
And then, of course, we got computers in our department.
Everybody thought that we should get computerized in that course.

which I was reluctant to do because I felt that the students should know how to do this by hand, and that particularly with the cohort survival technique, that they might lose one of the essential attributes of the technique in not cranking in changes in migration rates by cohort

or survival rates or whatever, and that they would just simply punch a button and the computer would assume everything would stay the same and it would grind out numbers, which is exactly what happened after I was almost forced to go to computer on it by outside pressures in the department.
So it happened, and I predicted it would, and I think that it was a mistake to do that.

the computers to be used at all, I think it should be at the end of the semester where it's a hands-on sort of thing and the students are required to make changes in migration rights and birth and death rates and so forth.
cohort and by time increment.

You know, I don't use computer in that course exactly for, partly for that reason and partly because up to now there is no good packages available to do that, to do gravity model, to do land use model, etc.
And even if become available, I guess that would be another course that, OK, we covered the theory.
Now let us go and do applied in the computer.
Personally, I don't want to spend time of learning those computer things.
Every day, they are changing all these packages.
But I guess if ever I was forced to do the same way, I'd have to do something about it.
I think for us as the planners, it's more important to understand the concepts.
And if we really need to use it, we can always go ahead and learn the packages.
And especially that nowadays, they try to put the packages in a way that one can learn by himself.
So they can go and learn it and apply it.
Taking a look at the future of planning education in Texas, do you see any changes in the whole system of having three certified programs?
You know, I know that we have three programs which may look a little small for such a big state.
But on the other hand, I believe that none of the schools has been too big to justify any other program.
As far as I know, all three programs have had only a handful of students.
Am I right?
I think so.
Well, we usually have, at any one time, around 65 to 70 enrolled.
In master program or?
Well, in all three degree programs.
We have the Master of Science in Land Development, the MUP, and the PhD.
But if you put the PhD separate, and perhaps in the land development a little bit separate, you are going to have about 40, am I right?
40 is not, I mean, 40 you and perhaps about 30, 40...
If we stay with 40 that we are now, it would be 120.
And I remember coming from Los Angeles area, in Los Angeles alone, there were three, four planning programs.
Each one of them, at least UCLA and USC, I believe, had about 50, 60 each.
And then there was Cal Poly program that had 150 students or something.
Pomona one.
And then there was that private school I forgot which the name of the program wasn't directly planning, it was something like public administration.
Pepperdine?
Pepperdine.
They had some students there too.
So one metropolitan area almost having twice of all our students.
So in some sense I don't think that we need more schools, at least for now.
But on the other hand, I believe that this growth which happened in Texas happened so fast that so many of the communities couldn't realize that they needed planners to handle that.
But now that the wave is gone and they have seen how much mistakes they have done, hopefully they realize that they have done mistakes.
Some of them I'm sure they won't realize.
Some of them are realizing now and they are starting to hire or to feel that gradually they need to have such staff there.
So I feel that gradually, very slowly, the demand for planners is going to increase a little bit, at least in the public sector, especially in cities and counties, et cetera.

if that trend is correct then perhaps we're going to have a little bit more demand but that doesn't to me that doesn't mean that we're going to have 100 students each or something means that we're going to move from 40 to 50 because we are talking about stable type of situations but in regard to what area
we'll need to cover for those things.

Of course, one area is just dealing with the growth and managing the urban areas, because it is traditional in Texas that so many areas have just used to manage the urban areas without planning, or even without zoning, as the case of Houston, etc.
And gradually, I think,
these things would, the wave has started, of course, years ago to come from west and east to here.
And if we consider that trend, we're going to see that more cities are going to have formal planning organizations or counties.
So there is a need in that side to be fulfilled.
I think we have a mission to teach actual practice of planning in terms of physical planning, that they go and do it.
On the other hand, there are all the new areas of planning, which has been, I don't know, the output of, say, 60s and 70s.
And perhaps in some regions, it's starting to come down and semi-die off.
Some of those ways are going to come here, like social planning a little bit, or I don't know, other health planning.

other discussions which may not be directly a core area of planning or physical planning or so and those I think being already discovered by different communities and organizations even private sector one as we were talking real estate etc I think there is also demand there that we got to try to fulfill those so overall the way I see planning here and
I think that we should gear up to train people for both of those, both the public side, which is the actual physical planning side, but also the other social and art things.
We have one student that graduated with a clear idea of going into institutional planning.
I didn't quite know what he meant by that.
I don't know what you're talking about.
But what he wanted to do was actually restructure organizations and to look at them from an effectiveness point of view.
And he started out in the New Orleans school district.
So there are all sorts of little niches that people can move into.
The question that has come up with Paul that perhaps the three accredited schools can't teach every specialty and that maybe we ought to get together and identify what the needs of Texas are.
And then separate the area.
And then who has what kinds of current capabilities
and then draw some conclusions from that.
And we already have a cooperative agreement with the University of Texas at Austin.
And that, frankly, is on paper only.
It doesn't seem to be functioning very well.
Which is what?
Pardon?
Which is what?
That a student can take a course at the University of Texas
If it is similar to what offered at A&M, they can take it, for example, during the summertime if they are in an internship there.
And we can include it in their degree program for credit at A&M, which seems only logical.
But logic does not prevail in academia.
Yeah, especially by the way of funding.
I don't know how is your funding system, but I believe it would be very similar to ours.
Eventually, we are one type of system, I think.
If you are going to create ours, you've got to naturally try to keep all the created ours for yourself, and that would create the problem.
Sure.
So it's a problem.
We ran into all sorts of red tape with this one particular student.
Not all of it because of the institutional arrangements, some of it was because of the enthusiasm of the student in moving ahead of the ability of the organizational structure to handle it.
But these sorts of things can be worked out, it seems to me.
And not that I think that there's an advantage of having multiple schools and planning.
And I also think that UT Arlington is geographically situated the best of any of them.
Yeah, because the other one is in Austin, and there's nothing in Houston.
You are the closest one to Houston.
Well, Texas Southern.
But they are not accurate.
Do they have a planning program?
Essentially no longer.
That, it's...
predominantly Negro college, and John Shanahan taught there for a while, but he's no longer with them.
Are there any thoughts that you want to include that we haven't already touched on?
Not really at this moment.
Just come to my mind later.
Okay, well, you'll be getting a transcript of this whenever
It's completed.
Sure.
And then you can go over it again and make any notations you wish.
Okay.
Thank you very much.
Thank you.
This is June 19, 1987.
We are in the office of Dr. Joel Goldstein at the University of Texas in Arlington.
Joel, let's begin with your background, your education, your first professional work, and then how it came that you landed at Arlington.
Let's go back in history.
I was an undergraduate to a bachelor's degree in architecture from the University of Pennsylvania in Philadelphia.
and was an assistant for a number of planning professors and courses, a work assistant as an undergraduate.
Got interested in planning, took planning courses, had joint studios with Paul Davidoff and Ian McCarr and a bunch of others.
Was Myerson there then?
Yes.
Everybody was there.
Dykman, Wheaton.
Yes.
The golden era.
Right.
The golden era.
I got interested in planning and knew that I wasn't going to... What was the date you got your architecture degree?
June 1963.
And it was...
I knew that I wasn't going to just be an architect with my professional planning degree.
I was going to get a professional planning degree someday or other.
And I ended up working and practicing and getting licensed in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania first.
I'm taking the licensing exam for New Jersey, no reciprocity across the river.
I take the exam all over again.
I'm licensed in New Jersey as an architect, and I look for graduate schools.
It was after about six years of practice in Philadelphia.
Okay.
And ended up looking at

schools and ended up getting a master's in urban design at Washington University in St. Louis, spending about a year there on campus, and then went for a couple of years to Tulsa, Oklahoma to run a community design center in a black neighborhood in a low-income Indian neighborhood in Tulsa for a couple of years.
What year was that?
That was 1969-70.
And during that time, I lived in Tulsa, worked at the design center, and commuted to Stillwater three days a week for classes, other classes I was responsible for as a faculty member.
And worked in Citizens Action there, and then more or less had a better offer in Detroit and went on the faculty of the University of Detroit.
as an associate professor, jumping rank from assistant to associate.
And at the same time, worked in the profession as second in charge of architectural design and chief planner for Giffles Associates in Detroit, the third largest AE firm in the world.
Flew all around the country doing projects while I was on the faculty.
at the University of Detroit, teaching planning, urban design, and architecture.
Sounds like a good combination.
Yeah, it was for a couple of years, and then I took my PhD while I was doing all of that.
And ended up, about the five years I was in Detroit, the last three years, not teaching at University of Detroit, but just doing my PhD in Giffles Associates.

and got my PhD at Michigan State University, East Lansing, in urban and regional planning with cognate areas in social psychology and political science, social change, studying psychology and psychometric, psychological statistics.
Strange combination.
So you moved away from physical design.
Totally into this social planning.
Then I was offered the job here to come in as the first director of the planning program in the School of Architecture.
Probably in 1975, fall of 1975, as their first director of the planning program.
the new planning program here at UT Arlington.
That's when we met.
Right.
And one thing, as an inexperienced planning professor at this school, inexperienced with Texas, I began to learn and practice in my spare time when I wasn't involved with university duties.
Dallas-Fort Worth and big projects around the country.
Taking a look at the program here, what would you say are its strong points and its weak points?
Strong ones first.
Definite strong points is its balanced
balanced emphasis towards development and cities.
In other words, the social aspects, the residents, are not seen as
black hats or white hats.
The developers are not seen as black hats or white hats.
Both sides seem to be taught by the faculty as being equally as important.
The balance is there.
Number two, I think that the strong point is that as a commuting school, the only one in the region that we know of, by region I mean broad, let's say six, seven, eight state regions,
where are primarily a commuting school, a night program.

And that's a strength because in the tight times of planning jobs in this almost 12 years that I've been here, it has given students an opportunity to enroll in a planning program, get their first job while a student,
and graduate with two or three years experience by the time they finish their coursework and they've graduated.
So they're already working in their job when they graduate.
Or they're moving to their second job with two or three years experience.
So I think that's very strong.
Yeah, it has benefits in the classroom, too.
Yes, it does.
There's lots of war stories that get told.
And there's a lot of networking that the students do between each other in the classroom.
The disadvantages are the same thing.
Those commuting students are tired from having worked all day.
They come in the classroom at night, 7 o'clock at night.
Many of them can't keep their head up because they've been studying hard the nights before in preparation for classwork.
And you can't go as late as you'd like.
What about the faculty?
Faculty are sleepy, too.
Demands on the faculty.

Faculty, if you teach two nights a week, which is our typical teaching load, until 10.30 at night, from 7 to 10.30, the pressures, the social pressures of the job are to be in your office all during the day.
And if you're not in in the morning, the other faculty kind of wander.
So there's a lot of pressure, so you end up with a lot of
unproductive time because you're so physically tired.
It is not the ideal academic situation.
It's great for students.
It's been great for students.
The way the economy is, it's been bad for faculty.
In terms of the substance of the curriculum here in your Master of City and Regional Planning degree,
How do you feel that this compares with other master's degrees in planning around the countryside?
I would say that a number of schools we've heard about, your side, not with checking, they have their actual, any kind of, running any actual testing of their graduates or anything.
appears many of them are just social welfare planning oriented programs.
Some of the others are strictly public agency training kinds of programs as a result of accreditation guidelines.
I think where we kind of have succeeded over the years is that we're trying to train people
to go into real estate and land development jobs as well as consulting jobs in addition to the public sector traditional planning jobs.
And because of the job market the way it is in the metro area, the job opportunities have existed.
And we have a number of students that have entered our program and worked for major developers, major national developers.
Dallas-Fort Worth has the advantage of having some
the most major development companies in the United States and Canada here.
So it's been a confluence of real estate and land development dollars for the United States.
They've spilled in here from Germany, from Canada, bounce in Dallas, Fort Worth, and then spill over into Houston, California, to Chicago.
So there's been a bouncing effect.
So there's been an opportunity for our students to get to work for the banking community, the financial institutions,
as well as the real estate and land development community.
So that the planning accreditation guidelines of having this public sector base begins to get broadened through the way that we've been teaching in our classes.
There's no doubt about it, your location is very advantageous for an urban planner.
certainly much better than Austin or College Station.
Next year you are facing the visiting team from the Accreditation Committee of APA.
Recently we underwent such an examination and it resulted in some changes in our core curriculum.
Do you anticipate any such changes to your curriculum or structure?
I would say the curriculum has been just worked on over the past two or three years in creating a new program that was just initiated about a year ago.
I don't think that any fault will be found in the new program by the accreditation team.
I think there may be some structural changes according to the way the planning program has been
administered in to the Institute of Urban Studies that go negatively to the guidelines for accreditation.
Well then it might help the program quite a bit by having the outside comments.
I believe so.
Politically I don't really wish to elaborate on that.
Okay, we'll go on to another topic.
Regarding the future of Texas and particularly planning for the future in Texas, do you see any changes in the offing in regard to planning education to meet any possible changes?
I think the most critical thing today is learning to effectively infiltrate citizens groups
to create behavioral change, that planning is being stopped by residents.
Any kind of change is being affected.
City budgets are being affected by residents.
The not in my backyard syndrome is rampant with all the displacees that have come here to make their fortunes, to live in the Dallas-Fort Worth area and into Texas.
People are settling in.

And I think that it's almost going to have to be for the same kind of citizens' action kinds of activities by planners into the 90s, the 1990s, that are going to be very similar to the 60s of the years of social planning, social welfare planning, for opposite reasons.
A rebirth of advocacy planning?
Not advocacy, but let's say reverse advocacy planning.
in favor of pro-development in order for people to be able to get through the economic conditions of the times.
In other words, I see fiscal stress due to a federal deficit, budget deficit, and people having less and less discretionary income.
As a result of that, they can very well benefit by planning, by having sound fiscal planning that is through effective pro-development postures

being to their ultimate advantage, that planning on the basis of what people want for them, they may not, they need to be led to what they should have through professionalism, more of an elitist attitude, but yet through a participatory mode.
It's interesting.

Paul Geisel, in answer to that question, felt that planning had resurrected its good name, which came to me as a surprise because I think that in our area of Texas and College Station and East Central Texas, planning is still a dirty word.
But he felt that in the Metroplex area,
that because of citizen participation and citizen planning of neighborhoods, that planning had again become quite a positive force and had achieved a new degree of respect.

I think there's a respect there, but I think the respect is there on the part of the local elected officials who are running all the land use decision-making, because they can hide behind it effectively from a legal perspective and make their own self-interest decisions.
So I think that's where planning may be considered resurrected in the minds of the elected officials.
As far as actual planning goes, I think not.
I think that they're clearly doing themselves in with exclusionary planning and exclusionary zoning without planning.
Without planning, yes, which is conceptually an unacceptable procedure.
Absolutely.
they certainly wouldn't be able to get away with that in Oregon, where planning has mattered.
Or Michigan, or Wisconsin, or Florida, Pennsylvania, which isn't as strong as other states, and on and on, Tennessee.
Planning has been very undeveloped in Texas.
And you can see it and you can feel it when you operate in the arena of planning.
It's clear.
It's been undeveloped.
There's been no traditional planning that I can put my finger on except for Fort Worth, Texas.

Fort Worth has had the tradition because it's been almost like a city of beautiful activity by the elite who have been dilettantes in the planning since the 54 Victor Gruen plant and going back even earlier than that.
I haven't written about Fort Worth yet, but I have written about El Paso.
And El Paso's planning program got started in 1919.
And they've been doing it ever since.
In fact, there's a question about whether or not their city council was the first in the country to adopt a comprehensive plan that was professionally formulated.
One usually thinks that this happened in 1925 in, was it Cincinnati?
I think it was Cincinnati.
With Bettman?
Yes, with Bettman and others.
And the question I'm going to have to research is the exact date on which all city councils took action.
Because it might be that El Paso, we might have to rewrite history.
When I first began here in 1975, the dean was Dean Hal Box, who was an architect and was in practice in Dallas with the two others.
Architectural.
Architectural practice.
And Hal Box was dean for approximately a year
during my time to a year and a half, I forget exactly which, but sometime either fall of 76 or spring of 77 he left to become dean of UT Austin.
At that time an acting dean, or interim dean, was George Wright,
for about a year or two, and they had a search, and the university selected George Wright to be the new dean.
George Wright stayed there.
Another architect?
Another architect from Albuquerque.
They'd been in an unsuccessful practice in Albuquerque.
And he had been an assistant to Hal Box, and that's how he basically got it.
Older man, the oldest person on the faculty just about, so therefore you must know something because he's of age.
And what then happened was that planning was considered a program
with a shared budget with a landscape architecture program, architecture and interior design.
The numbers were misbalanced and all of the undergraduates selecting a major were advised by architecture professors.
Sounds like A&M.
So the architecture professors steered, in my opinion, steered
students into architecture, the bulk was in architecture, a very few in number or interior design, and planning got, did not get their share in the undergraduate emphasis.
As far as the graduate program went, we were left alone, but we shared budgets with architecture and planning, graduate.
Our first students were... Is that still the situation?
No, let me give you the history.
Upon applying for accreditation and working with it, the former dean, Dean Wright, gave separate budgeting power and autonomy of program to the planning program.
And we obtained our accreditation, I believe, in 77 or 78, remarkably quick.
because of their support.

And we had four years within the School of Architecture, and during that time, the planning faculty, Gene Brooks and a fellow named Barry Rubin, who was a graduate of the University of Wisconsin, and some graduate students,
of ours made a political move to get planning out of the School of Architecture and successfully moved it out of architecture, succeeded in doing so, and moved it into the graduate school.
Jean Brooks stayed behind in the School of Architecture as a teacher of undergraduate urban design
Barry Rubin got a distaste for the university and left to go to the University of Indiana to teach planning.
So we were under the graduate dean as an interdisciplinary program for two years with a sociologist for a department chairman.
who had been appointed by new disciplinary planning faculty.
Who was that?

That was Lee Taylor, L-E-E-T-A-Y-L-O-R. Lee Taylor's interest was Newtowns as a sociologist, and at the end of two years, we clearly did not have faculty representation on campus on any committees, faculty senate,
and all that.
And the dean of the graduate school had us as the only academic unit under his tutelage.
So he didn't want us.
So we were asked to recommend a place on campus.
Vice President for Academic Affairs went to our faculty, and we agreed with his recommendation to come into the Institute of Urban Studies, which we are now.
We came in as a full-fledged department.
with accreditation.
We had an accreditation team visit within two years.
At that time, which was about six years thereafter of me coming here, I again became chairman of the Department of City and Regional Planning.
At this time it was a department.
It was a department for a full year, and the dean made a decision that there would be no departments, that we would be called a program.
So my business cards went from chairman to director.
And there were directors of criminal justice, director of urban affairs, director of city and regional planning.
That was, we had...
We had a space on the second floor of University Hall that was just city and regional planning.
We were not integrated with the Institute of Urban Studies on the fifth floor.
We were separate and distinct from the very high visibility portion of the building where everyone could see us up at the stairwell.
And we succeeded to gain in enrollments and we were doing just fine.
The dean made a decision to
integrate us fully with the institute of urban studies well you the dean had just asked you to take the job as chairman and you declined and i declined i had some research interest and i
felt that for my own professional academic career, it was time for me to work toward promotion to full professor level.
And I had also some interesting outside consulting projects directly related to my university teaching.
Comprehensive plans for communities to do, advisory to different cities on urban design matters, and some ordinance writing.
So you continued on as a teaching professor without administrative responsibilities.
Which is where I am now.
And who took over as department chairman?
Well, it appears from what has been said that the dean of the Institute of Urban Studies has.
There was no department chairman.
Has not been for two years.
What will happen when the APA
accreditation team visits, and they discover you have no department head.
I would assume that that will be one of the items that they write up as being a deficiency.
I would think so, too.
And do you have control over your budget currently?
No, the dean controls the budget.
When did that change?
That changed when I was no longer
when he eliminated all the directors in the Institute of Urban Studies.
And does he understand the consequences of that?
It had been explained to him.
As far as the day-to-day operations of the department go,
You mentioned that Arj Anjamani is in charge of the graduate studies.
He is graduate advisor.
Advisor.
And what does Bob Wagner do these days?
Bob Wagner teaches in the planning program, teaches courses in the planning program, graduate, and he works on the Texas chapter APA newsletter.
And he is working as an editor on the Texas Planning Magazine, which had been at A&M University.
He's quite busy.
And he also does training courses for lay planning practitioners.
Lay planners, rather.
There's some question in my mind about whether or not that is in competition with the short course offered by the Texas chapter.
I think that it is not because it ends up being a special course for one community that he'll travel down to.
If the vehicle, the annual short course is a large operation.
where people come from all over the country, all over the state, rather.
I really don't think that it is in competition.
At first I thought that, but not since I've seen some of his attendance lists.
I think a lot would depend upon the material covered.
It varies.
Sometimes he's talking to them about capital budgets.
Sometimes it's strictly about what planning is and why you should plan.
Other times it's about ordinances.
Well, we certainly don't need to have any paucity of spreading the word about planning.
The fiscal condition of the University of Texas at Arlington has been abysmal for the last five years as far as planning goes and the Institute of Urban Studies.
Faculty raises have not been of any substance whatsoever.
They've been less than Texas A&M and UT Austin.
And the raises, the faculty raises, have been demoralizing and insulting.
